Paragraph: (1) It was resolved to act with energy. (2) The deputy police inspector of the town was commissioned to take four witnesses, to enter Fyodor Pavlovitch’s house and there to open an inquiry on the spot, according to the regular forms, which I will not go into here. (3) The district doctor, a zealous man, new to his work, almost insisted on accompanying the police captain, the prosecutor, and the investigating lawyer. (4) I will note briefly that Fyodor Pavlovitch was found to be quite dead, with his skull battered in. (5) But with what? (6) Most likely with the same weapon with which Grigory had been attacked. (7) And immediately that weapon was found, Grigory, to whom all possible medical assistance was at once given, described in a weak and breaking voice how he had been knocked down. (8) They began looking with a lantern by the fence and found the brass pestle dropped in a most conspicuous place on the garden path. (9) There were no signs of disturbance in the room where Fyodor Pavlovitch was lying. (10) But by the bed, behind the screen, they picked up from the floor a big and thick envelope with the inscription: “A present of three thousand roubles for my angel Grushenka, if she is willing to come.” And below had been added by Fyodor Pavlovitch, “For my little chicken.” There were three seals of red sealing‐wax on the envelope, but it had been torn open and was empty: the money had been removed. (11) They found also on the floor a piece of narrow pink ribbon, with which the envelope had been tied up. (12) One piece of Pyotr Ilyitch’s evidence made a great impression on the prosecutor and the investigating magistrate, namely, his idea that Dmitri Fyodorovitch would shoot himself before daybreak, that he had resolved to do so, had spoken of it to Ilyitch, had taken the pistols, loaded them before him, written a letter, put it in his pocket, etc. (13) When Pyotr Ilyitch, though still unwilling to believe in it, threatened to tell some one so as to prevent the suicide, Mitya had answered grinning: “You’ll be too late.” So they must make haste to Mokroe to find the criminal, before he really did shoot himself. (14) “That’s clear, that’s clear!” repeated the prosecutor in great excitement. (15) “That’s just the way with mad fellows like that: ‘I shall kill myself to‐ morrow, so I’ll make merry till I die!’ ”



The story of how he had bought the wine and provisions excited the prosecutor more than ever. (16) “Do you remember the fellow that murdered a merchant called Olsufyev, gentlemen? (17) He stole fifteen hundred, went at once to have his hair curled, and then, without even hiding the money, carrying it almost in his hand in the same way, he went off to the girls.”



All were delayed, however, by the inquiry, the search, and the formalities, etc., in the house of Fyodor Pavlovitch. (18) It all took time and so, two hours before starting, they sent on ahead to Mokroe the officer of the rural police, Mavriky Mavrikyevitch Schmertsov, who had arrived in the town the morning before to get his pay. (19) He was instructed to avoid raising the alarm when he reached Mokroe, but to keep constant watch over the “criminal” till the arrival of the proper authorities, to procure also witnesses for the arrest, police constables, and so on. (20) Mavriky Mavrikyevitch did as he was told, preserving his incognito, and giving no one but his old acquaintance, Trifon Borissovitch, the slightest hint of his secret business. (21) He had spoken to him just before Mitya met the landlord in the balcony, looking for him in the dark, and noticed at once a change in Trifon Borissovitch’s face and voice. (22) So neither Mitya nor any one else knew that he was being watched. (23) The box with the pistols had been carried off by Trifon Borissovitch and put in a suitable place. (24) Only after four o’clock, almost at sunrise, all the officials, the police captain, the prosecutor, the investigating lawyer, drove up in two carriages, each drawn by three horses. (25) The doctor remained at Fyodor Pavlovitch’s to make a post‐mortem next day on the body. (26) But he was particularly interested in the condition of the servant, Smerdyakov. (27) “Such violent and protracted epileptic fits, recurring continually for twenty‐four hours, are rarely to be met with, and are of interest to science,” he declared enthusiastically to his companions, and as they left they laughingly congratulated him on his find. (28) The prosecutor and the investigating lawyer distinctly remembered the doctor’s saying that Smerdyakov could not outlive the night. (29) After these long, but I think necessary explanations, we will return to that moment of our tale at which we broke off.



